<div class="study-container">

  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>Marsh & McLennan (MMC) Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p>A transparent, step-by-step discounted cash flow valuation using FY2025 actuals. We reveal every number, calculation, and assumption so you can see exactly how we arrived at fair value.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ VERDICT CARD ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="vc-title">Intrinsic Value Estimate</div>
    <div class="vc-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="vc-stat-value" style={`color: ${verdictColor}; margin-top: 0.5rem; font-size: 1.2rem;`}>
      {verdictText} (Margin of safety: {marginOfSafety}%)
    </div>

    <div class="vc-compare">
      <div class="vc-stat">
        <span class="vc-stat-label">Current Price</span>
        <span class="vc-stat-value" style="color: #ffffff;">${currentPrice.toFixed(2)}</span>
      </div>
      <div class="vc-stat">
        <span class="vc-stat-label">FY2025 FCF</span>
        <span class="vc-stat-value" style="color: #10b981;">${(fcf2025 / 1000).toFixed(2)}B</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p><strong>The TL;DR:</strong> Marsh & McLennan generated $5.0B in Free Cash Flow in FY2025. If they can grow that cash flow at 8% annually for the next 5 years, and 3% in perpetuity thereafter, the business is worth roughly <strong>${roundedIV.toFixed(2)} per share</strong> today (assuming a 9% discount rate). Compared to the current price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)}, the stock appears {verdictText.toLowerCase()}.</p>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY & ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology & Assumptions</h2>
  <p>We use a standard <strong>Two-Stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF)</strong> model. The logic is simple: a company is only worth the total cash it will generate over its lifetime, discounted back to today's dollars.</p>

  <div class="assumptions-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="ac-title">Years 1-5 Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="ac-value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100)}%</div>
      <div class="ac-desc">Marsh & McLennan's FCF grew by an impressive 25% in FY2025, but normalized long-term trends have historically hovered around high single-digits. We assume 8% forward FCF growth, reflecting their strong pricing power in insurance brokerage and solid consulting demand, tempered by base effects.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="ac-title">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="ac-value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100)}%</div>
      <div class="ac-desc">After Year 5, we assume the company grows at 3% forever. This aligns with long-term global GDP inflation and base economic growth. No company can outgrow GDP forever.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="ac-title">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="ac-value">{(discountRate * 100)}%</div>
      <div class="ac-desc">With the 10-Year Treasury at 4.18%, we use a 9% discount rate. MMC operates a highly capital-light, recession-resistant business with sticky recurring revenues. This low-risk profile justifies a discount rate slightly below the 10% average.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Step 1: Projecting Cash Flows</h2>
  <p>Starting with FY2025's actual Free Cash Flow of $5,001M, we project 8% growth for the next five years. We then discount each year's cash flow back to present value using our 9% discount rate.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>Projected FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>Discount Factor (9%)</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr style="opacity: 0.6">
          <td style="text-align:left">Year 0 (FY2025 Actual)</td>
          <td>${fcf2025}</td>
          <td>1.000</td>
          <td>-</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td style="text-align:left">Year {p.year}</td>
            <td>${p.fcf}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(3)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3" style="text-align:left">Sum of Present Value (Years 1-5)</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h2>Step 2: The Terminal Value</h2>
  <p>Marsh & McLennan won't cease to exist after 5 years. The "Terminal Value" represents all cash flows generated from Year 6 to infinity, growing at 3%.</p>

  <p><strong>Math:</strong> (Year 5 FCF of ${projectedFCF[4].fcf}M × 1.03) / (0.09 - 0.03) = <strong>${terminalValue}M</strong>.</p>
  <p>Because that money is generated in the future, we must discount it back to today's dollars (multiplying by the Year 5 discount factor of {projectedFCF[4].pvFactor.toFixed(3)}).</p>
  <p><strong>Present Value of Terminal Value:</strong> <span class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue}M</span></p>

  <!-- ═══ FINAL CALCULATION ═══ -->
  <h2>Step 3: Equity Value to Per-Share Value</h2>
  <p>We add the present value of Years 1-5 to the present value of the terminal years to get the <strong>Enterprise Value</strong>. We then add MMC's cash and subtract its debt to find the <strong>Equity Value</strong>. Finally, divide by shares outstanding.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td>${pvTerminalValue}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total" style="background: transparent;">
          <td style="text-align:left">Enterprise Value</td>
          <td>${enterpriseValue}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Plus: Cash & Short-Term Investments</td>
          <td>${cashAndInvestments}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Less: Total Debt</td>
          <td>-${totalDebt}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total" style="background: transparent;">
          <td style="text-align:left">Total Equity Value</td>
          <td>${equityValue}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="text-align:left">Divided by Shares Outstanding</td>
          <td>{sharesOutstanding}M</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td style="text-align:left">Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ HISTORICAL CHARTS ═══ -->
  <h2>Financial Track Record</h2>
  <p>Consistency is key for insurance brokerages and consulting firms. Let's look at MMC's historical performance.</p>

  <h3>Revenue ($M)</h3>
  <div class="bar-chart">
    {revenueHistory.map(r => (
      <div class="bar-row">
        <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
        <div class="bar-track">
          <div class="bar-fill revenue" style={`width: ${(r.value / 26981) * 100}%`}>
            ${(r.value / 1000).toFixed(1)}B
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h3>Free Cash Flow ($M)</h3>
  <div class="bar-chart">
    {fcfHistory.map(r => (
      <div class="bar-row">
        <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
        <div class="bar-track">
          <div class="bar-fill fcf" style={`width: ${(r.value / 5001) * 100}%`}>
            ${(r.value / 1000).toFixed(1)}B
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h3>Earnings Per Share (Diluted)</h3>
  <div class="bar-chart">
    {epsHistory.map(r => (
      <div class="bar-row">
        <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
        <div class="bar-track">
          <div class="bar-fill eps" style={`width: ${(r.value / 8.43) * 100}%`}>
            ${r.value.toFixed(2)}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

