  <p><strong>Key observation:</strong> Operating margins and FCF margins have shown steady expansion over the past five years. The jump in FCF margin to 18.5% in 2025 demonstrates the scale efficiencies inherent in MMC's consulting and brokerage businesses.</p>

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Valuation is an estimate, not a science. See how the intrinsic value shifts if we tweak our assumptions for growth and discount rate.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={Math.abs(g - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={Math.abs(row.dr - discountRate) < 0.001 && Math.abs(sensitivityGrowth[i] - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Notice that due to MMC's debt load, higher discount rates heavily compress the fair equity value.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>A pure discounted cash flow model has blind spots. Here are qualitative factors that could swing the actual value of Marsh & McLennan.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Harder Insurance Markets:</strong> In a "hard market" where insurance premiums rise, brokers like MMC generate higher commissions without proportionate cost increases. If inflation remains sticky, premiums and commissions will stay elevated.</li>
    <li><strong>Acquisition Synergies:</strong> MMC is a serial acquirer (Marsh McLennan Agency). If they accelerate roll-ups of smaller brokerages at attractive multiples, FCF growth could comfortably exceed 8%.</li>
    <li><strong>Consulting Boom:</strong> Mercer and Oliver Wyman segments could see higher-than-expected demand due to complex global risks (geopolitics, AI integration, restructuring).</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Economic Contraction:</strong> While insurance is defensive, Oliver Wyman (management consulting) is highly sensitive to corporate budgets and economic cycles. A deep recession could crater consulting revenue.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> With $21.4B in total debt, MMC uses leverage to enhance returns. In a prolonged high-interest-rate environment, refinancing this debt will eat into free cash flow.</li>
    <li><strong>Soft Insurance Markets:</strong> If insurance pricing cycle turns "soft" (premiums fall), commission revenues will naturally decline, compressing margins.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an 8% growth rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While FY2025 saw massive FCF growth, MMC's normalized historical growth is closer to the high single digits. We chose 8% as a conservative base case that reflects their durable competitive advantage, continuous bolt-on acquisitions, and pricing power, while acknowledging they operate from a larger base.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the Enterprise Value so different from Equity Value?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">MMC carries a significant amount of debt ($21.4B) compared to cash ($2.6B). In a DCF, the cash flows value the whole business (Enterprise Value), but to find the value of the shares (Equity Value), we must pay off the debt. This $18.7B net debt subtracts heavily from the intrinsic value per share.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why a 9% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate reflects risk. MMC's revenues are highly sticky, recurring, and diversified across risk, strategy, and human capital consulting globally. Therefore, the business is "less risky" than an average stock, justifying a slightly lower required rate of return than the standard 10%.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy or sell recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Neither. This is a mathematical exercise to find a baseline intrinsic value using explicitly stated assumptions. It is up to you to decide if the current market price offers a sufficient margin of safety for your portfolio.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

